Dimention Reduction & Binary Classification in Employee Attrition Prediction

Dataset Information¶

Uncover the factors that lead to employee attrition and explore important questions such as show me a breakdown of distance from home by job role and attrition or compare average monthly income by education and attrition. This is a fictional data set created by IBM data scientists.

Attribute Information¶

Education: 1 'Below College', 2 'College', 3 'Bachelor', 4 'Master', 5 'Doctor'

EnvironmentSatisfaction: 1 'Low', 2 'Medium', 3 'High', 4 'Very High'

JobInvolvement: 1 'Low', 2 'Medium', 3 'High', 4 'Very High'

JobSatisfaction: 1 'Low', 2 'Medium', 3 'High', 4 'Very High'

PerformanceRating: 1 'Low', 2 'Good', 3 'Excellent', 4 'Outstanding'

RelationshipSatisfaction: 1 'Low', 2 'Medium', 3 'High', 4 'Very High'

WorkLifeBalance: 1 'Bad', 2 'Good', 3 'Better', 4 'Best'

Goal¶

Here, lets create classification model which feature were created from PCA only. The reason for choosing this approach were:

  1. Dataset contains lots of feature.
  2. Dataset contain several strongly correlated features.
  3. Tackle the curse of dimentionality, since fewer the dimentions involved in creating classification, the smaller the resource used, also lead to quicker time to train the model.

There were also lots of binary classification algorithm used even thou the author weren't completely lookup for the underlying assumption for each model, therefore this extra step just an addition for reference of python capabilities in creating model selection with looping.

Source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/pavansubhasht/ibm-hr-analytics-attrition-dataset

Principal Component Analysis

PCA Assumption¶

  1. PCA assumes a correlation between features. If the features (or dimensions or columns, in tabular data) are not correlated, PCA will be unable to determine principal components.

  2. PCA is sensitive to the scale of the features. Imagine we have two features - one takes values between 0 and 1000, while the other takes values between 0 and 1. PCA will be extremely biased towards the first feature being the first principle component, regardless of the actual maximum variance within the data. This is why its so important to standardize the values first.

  3. PCA is not robust against outliers. Similar to the point above, the algorithm will be biased in datasets with strong outliers. This is why it is recommended to remove outliers before performing PCA.

  4. PCA assumes a linear relationship between features. The algorithm is not well suited to capturing non-linear relationships. Thats why its advised to turn non-linear features or relationships between features into linear, using the standard methods such as log transforms.

  5. Technical implementations often assume no missing values. When computing PCA using statistical software tools, they often assume that the feature set has no missing values (no empty rows). Be sure to remove those rows and/or columns with missing values, or impute missing values with a close approximation (e.g. the mean of the column).

Source = https://www.keboola.com/blog/pca-machine-learning

Classification Applied

Here, let's try to create classification model with logistic regression

Logistic Regression Assumptions¶

  1. Logistic regression generally works as a classifier, so the type of logistic regression utilized (binary, multinomial, or ordinal) must match the outcome (dependent) variable in the dataset.

  2. The relationship between the logit (aka log-odds) of the outcome and each continuous independent variable is linear.

  3. Logistic regression assumes that there are no highly influential outlier data points, as they distort the outcome and accuracy of the model.

  4. Multicollinearity corresponds to a situation where the data contain highly correlated independent variables. This is a problem because it reduces the precision of the estimated coefficients, which weakens the statistical power of the logistic regression model.

  5. The observations must be independent of each other, i.e., they should not come from repeated or paired data. This means that each observation is not influenced by or related to the rest of the observations.

  6. There should be an adequate number of observations for each independent variable in the dataset to avoid creating an overfit model.

Source = https://towardsdatascience.com/assumptions-of-logistic-regression-clearly-explained-44d85a22b290

1. Logistic Regression Must Match the Outcome¶

Since here the dependent variable were consist of Yes and No, we use binary classification

2. The Relationship between Logit of the Outcome and Continous Independent Variables were Linear¶

In [ ]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score

accuracy, precision, recall = {}, {}, {}

for key in models.keys():
    
    # Fit the classifier
    models[key].fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    # Make predictions
    predictions = models[key].predict(X_test)
    
    # Calculate metrics
    accuracy[key] = accuracy_score(predictions, y_test)
    precision[key] = precision_score(predictions, y_test)
    recall[key] = recall_score(predictions, y_test)
In [ ]:
df_model = pd.DataFrame(index=models.keys(), columns=['Accuracy', 'Precision', 'Recall'])

df_model['Precision'] = precision.values()
df_model['Recall'] = recall.values()

With iterating the model implemented with input dataset, it may be more appropriate too look at accuracy and recall, the accuracy shows how many observation our model correctly predicted. The second one is recall, this is because I assumed that as an HR, we wouldn't want to miss any employee that may be resign and also having less concern if the employee actually doesn't planning to quit.

Based on those two logic, I might say that that tree based algorithm might be the right algorithm to develop. Since we want to maximize accuracy and recall, Random Forest algorithm may be choosen.

Random forest also has no formal distribution assumption, can handle skewed data, multi-modal data, as well as categorical data such as ordinal and non-ordinal data. Since the assumption were fulfilled with the curent training dataset, later I can further honed the Random Forest by parameter tuning it.

At the end of the analysis, in order to do binary classification analysis, fisrt I use PCA to reduce the dimentions of the data that previously contain 35 features (17 categorical and 18 numerical columns), down to 4 features (3 PCA generated independent feature and 1 dependent variable). Second, with profiding 4 features to train the model, I can produce model which has accuracy of 72.6% and recall 82.9%
